40 Year Reunion Announcement
Idalou High School Class of 1980
Classmates -
2020 is a year to remember.
COVID, Election, Hurricanes, Riots, Event Cancellations.
AND
THE CLASS OF 1980 40 YEAR REUNION IS ON!

No worries - if you don't feel comfortable coming - that's ok!
Schedule:
Friday, September 11
Class gathering at Janet and Buckles Bryant Home 6:30 - ?

Saturday, September 12
Our class will have a flat-bed trailer/float for the Cottonfest parade - meet at 9am to get on the float at Idalou Vista Bank

Saturday, September 12
Shrimp boil at Gary and Kaci Tucker's Home

There will not be a raffle this year - Donations are encouraged for our class fund and our reunion gift back to the school. Our donation will go to the Senior Trip.

Questions?
Message me or call 214-215-5487 - Kevin Noble

post_text: We all would like to say a huge THANK YOU to our local churches, First Baptist Idalou, Idalou Church of Christ, Idalou Methodist, St. Philip Benizi Catholic Church, and City Bank, for feeding us during our teacher inservice days. The food was delicious and the warm smiles that greeted us were so needed, but the thoughtful hands that organized and prepared our meals are the most meaningful. We thank you for the prayers as we begin this unusual school year tomorrow. We are so grateful for the community spirit shown to our staff and we are ready to love on our Wildcat students! Bless you all!

shared_text:
Michael Collins is with Robin Hutson and Charlotte Robertson.
July 7 at 7:42 PM ¬∑

The advisors of the Idalou FFA Chapter are extremely proud of all of our FFA members and the resilience, dedication and hard work that they have shown through the years but especially this spring and summer, when much of their activities were canceled and taken away from them. We are also proud that two of our FFA members received TX FFA scholarships (Desirae Randall and Channing shields). We are proud of Bailey Bozeman for receiving a National FFA scholarship. Bryce Hutson and Cash Campbell qualified for the state public speaking events. Taylor Criswell, Bryce Hutson, Jessie howle, Jenna Howle and Macey Owens received the Texas FFA Degree. Kelsey Collins, Logan Cooper and Everett Herrington will receive their American FFA Degree this fall from the National FFA Organization. Thanks Idalou FFA members for continuing to representing your families, school and community!

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

Graduation Ceremony Update!

Yesterday at 4:30 PM the Commissioner released strict guidelines about graduation ceremonies to Texas superintendents. We have been waiting for these guidelines to finalize our graduation plans. We now know that the earliest graduation ceremony date option is now June 1st. We are finalizing our graduation ceremony plans and senior trip plans for the first week of June. We hope to share specifics by this Friday!

Thank you for your patience! We have been waiting for these guidelines so we were confident in our plan! We also know that under our circumstances it could change again. We are working hard to plan the best celebration for our Idalou Wildcats Class of 2020! üíöüíõ

post_text: With the uncertainty surrounding the Corona virus, Idalou ISD is encouraging families to restrict their travel over spring break. Currently, the Lubbock Health Department does not have any cases of COVID-19 in our area. Yet, there are cases where many of you may be traveling. We encourage you to stay home, rest, and enjoy your families. We are monitoring the situation and will make whatever decision is best in the interest of our students and faculty in relation to their safety.

post_text:
HS One Act Play Encore Performance:
Tomorrow 3-4-20, 3:40 p.m., ‚ÄúVille Du Havre‚Äù
For those who were not able to attend last night, we will have an encore performance (aka dress rehearsal) on Wednesday 3/4 at 3:40. The play is about 40 minutes so we should be done no later than 4:30. This performance is free and open to the public.
The story is one of faith through adversity and how peace was found through a relationship with God. The lyrics ‚ÄúWhen peace like a river attendeth my way. When sorrows like sea billows roll‚Äù set the tone for how this story begins. Later, Spafford‚Äôs words ‚ÄúIt is well, It is well with my soul‚Äù express the peace that he receives from God despite his overwhelming circumstances.

The City of Idalou will test the Emergency Warning System Wednesday February 19th at 10:30 a.m. The testing will include the emergency warning sirens in the City. Testing will be conducted if weather conditions permit.
Alternate Test Date: Friday March 13th @ 10:30 a.m.

Note: If maintenance is necessary, there may be a need to perform repeated activation of the Emergency Warning System in order to troubleshoot and/or repair any system problems.
IN THE EVENT THAT THERE IS A FAILURE IN THE EMERGENCY WARNING SYSTEM, THE IDALOU POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WILL BE DRIVING AROUND THE CITY SOUNDING THEIR SIRENS ON HIGH-LOW.
IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CONTACT CITY HALL AT
892-2531.

Idalou High School Junior, Jenna Howle, is competing nationally in Breakaway Roping this weekend in Las Vegas, Nevada. Jenna participated in her first round of competition at the 2019 Vegas Tuffest Junior World Championship on Friday, December 16, 2019.
Jenna qualified to participate in this national event by winning sanctioned events in the summer of 2019. On Friday, Jenna competed in the first round and came in 5th place with a time of 3.08 seconds. The Breakaway Roping division Jenna competes in includes approximately 60 competitors who are from 43 different states and four Canadian provinces all vying for the chance to qualify for Sunday‚Äôs Short Go (finals.)

post_text:
Congratulations to Idalou HS Senior Madyson Cook for winning the South Plains Electric Cooperative Youth Tour Speech contest and will represent SPEC Lubbock by going to Washington, D.C. in June.

What: An all-expense-paid trip to Washington, D.C., to tour national historic sites, experience cultural diversity, meet U.S. congressional representatives, and learn about electric cooperatives and the energy industry

Who: High school students and their peers from around the nation who have won contests at their local electric cooperatives

Why: Because then-Sen. Lyndon B. Johnson, an advocate of rural electrification, suggested in 1957 ‚Äúsending youngsters to the national capital where they can actually see what the flag stands for and represents‚Äù

Where: Austin, Texas, and Washington, D.C.

When: 10 days in June

How: Students who win their electric co-op‚Äôs contest earn sponsorship valued at $3,265 for the trip, organized by Texas Electric Cooperatives and the National Rural Electric Cooperative Association

Idalou Elementary Thanksgiving Lunch
Monday 11-18-19 ~ PK 10:30, 1st grade 11:00, 3rd grade 11:30
Tuesday 11-19-19 ~ Kindergarten 10:30, 2nd grade 11:00, 4th grade 11:30
Adults $4.00, Children not in school $2.00

All checkins need to be by the cafeteria, not campus offices. A note was sent home asking you to let us know if you are coming. Please complete this information and send it back before this Friday.

If you are already in our Raptor ID system, your ID badge will be pre-printed and you may pick it up as you come in the cafeteria doors. If not, you will need to be prepared with your driver's license so we can scan you into our Raptor system and print you a badge. You will then proceed to pay by the doors. Please have cash and correct change; this will help speed things along.

We are looking forward to you visiting our campus.

post_text: These students are our fabulous Idalou Wildcat Band leadership:
shared_text:
City of Idalou
October 16, 2019 at 4:32 PM ¬∑

Today the Idalou Lions Club, had the pleasure hearing from Idalou High School Band members. They spoke of their passion for music and the leadership skills they have acquired being in band. They mentioned how each of their strengths helped make each other better. One band member said "Our differences make us one band". It's exciting to hear from students and we wish them well with their future endeavors.
